snippet.textDisplay: Whenever you do a head gasket you should take the head to a machine shop and have it pressure checked and resurfaced . Also whenever you have antifreeze mixed in with the oil there's a good chance the main and rod bearings will need replacing . Also if you pull the head off a motor and see cylinders that are clean and carbon free that usually means water has been getting into the cylindet or cylinders.

snippet.textDisplay: Cylinder heads and blocks may need to be resurfaced to restore flatness or to improve the surface finish. To seal properly, a head gasket requires a surface finish that is within a recommended range. If the surface is too rough, or in some cases too smooth, the gasket may not seal properly and leak or fail.  Try to resurfacing your cylinder head and block.

snippet.textDisplay:
It's an amazing feeling to be a new Apprentice Mechanic, because you understand so much more of the things these guys talk about when they tear car parts apart. I often have to check if head gaskets are leaking on vehicles from underneath, but I've never really seen one fully exposed like this yet so it was dope to see the little guy that can cost customers so much money. I love it, and I hope to be able to do things like these guys some day.


EDIT: I remember when I changed an Oil Cooler on a Dodge Grand Caravan and changed the oil on it afterwards, it came out exactly like at 20:41. It's because it was in fact like you guys were speculating that the coolant was flooding the oil. Also caused by a hairline fracture in the oil cooler, but it was over a much longer period of time (even though you guys DID have that oil in for over 8 hours).

snippet.textDisplay: You guys should of brought the head in to get machined. That's like a golden rule when doing headgaskets. And they can inspect the head while its there. And another thing to do is take the oil pan off and clean out that and also any coolant and oil passages to clear it from any mixed fluids. And the oil pump im sure is all nasty with that old mixed oil in there. So my best advice to you before blowing tons of money on a new engine is clean everything out really well and bring the head into the machine shop to get inspected and re decked. Good luck boys
snippet.textOriginal: You guys should of brought the head in to get machined. That's like a golden rule when doing headgaskets. And they can inspect the head while its there. And another thing to do is take the oil pan off and clean out that and also any coolant and oil passages to clear it from any mixed fluids. And the oil pump im sure is all nasty with that old mixed oil in there. So my best advice to you before blowing tons of money on a new engine is clean everything out really well and bring the head into the machine shop to get inspected and re decked. Good luck boys

snippet.textDisplay: Always and I mean always send the head to a machine shop to be checked and decked before putting it back together when a blow head gasket is done. Also when I, and yes I do rebuild engines a lot, do a major job like a head gasket like thus one I for sure pull the oil pan to clean all the old milky oil out and check the bottom end while in there. You might even want to replace the timing set while you're in there, it's pretty cheap insurance. Auto mechanics is a lot like life though and the best way to learn is through experience and I'm pretty sure you guys won't make that same mistake agian. Good luck boys

snippet.textDisplay: Hey guys. On this one you have been wrong from the beginning. First of all, never use powertools on head jobs. Then, tighten only at ARP specifications and not following the honda manual on this one as it will not work. Always use the gel given by ARP as this is extremely important for tightening torque. You should have dismantle all the engine to clean it from this "mayonnaise". Why? because all collant and oil tunnels are full of it and it is impossible to clean it by itself and will make anyway trouble. For your head surface, in fact, it could be warpped but as this is a petrol engine it does not happen so often, it is more on diesel engine as they have much more pressure. you should have it checked anyway. Finally, forget about boosting this engine, honda has made it extremely powerful already, it wont survive. PS: do not kick out the catalysor as you will have less power than if you leave it on. Cheers guys and good luck
